{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505425"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2440"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2440"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.61,0.09,0.19,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2440"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2440"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32282"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1311"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with severe headaches. They have been present more days than not for the past four months and are progressively getting more severe. There are no apparent triggers or preceding aura. She has no other health issues and is not on any medications. She does not smoke and drinks about a glass of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 115/70 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her BMI is 32. Fundoscopy shows swelling of the optic discs. Visual acuity and visual fields are normal. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A CT shows no abnormalities and a lumbar puncture is performed. This shows there is raised opening pressure (\u0026lt; 40 cm H2O).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sumatriptan","Acetazolamide","Intravenous ceftriaxone plus dexamethasone","Ventriculoperitoneal shunting","Optic nerve sheath fenestration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis history is characteristic of idiopathic intracranial hypertension (IIH) and the fundoscopic finding of papilloedema supports this diagnosis.  IIH causes a progressive accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid, which elevates intracranial pressure.The initial treatment is with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EVentriculoperitoneal shunting\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in IIH to relieve pressure when there is high risk of impending visual loss, which may be evidenced by reduced visual acuity and/or altered visual fields. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptic nerve sheath fenestration\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative option if there is no response to the acetazolamide.\u00a0This patient should also be encouraged to lose weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETriptans\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in the acute management of migraines, which would not cause raised opening pressure as in this case.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone plus dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is the empirical therapy for meningitis, which is not likely to be the diagnosis given the chronic nature of the headache.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial treatment of idiopathic intracranial hypertension should start with acetazolamide"],"references":["Mollan, S., Markey, K., Benzimra, J., Jacks, A., Matthews, T., Burdon, M. and Sinclair, A., 2014. A practical approach to, diagnosis, assessment and management of idiopathic intracranial hypertension. Practical Neurology, 14(6), pp.380-390."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32282"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2440"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32282"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-24T17:57:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-24T17:57:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2440"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47556"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data"